WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:03.120
Welcome to everybody. We're delighted to have you here for this session.

2
00:00:04.060 --> 00:00:05.700
It's a beautiful day outside,

3
00:00:07.120 --> 00:00:07.450
and

4
00:00:08.300 --> 00:00:11.940
reinforcing to our goal of keeping people healthy and preventing

5
00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:12.640
cancers

6
00:00:13.780 --> 00:00:14.960
as a supplement to the

7
00:00:15.820 --> 00:00:19.620
much larger effort on treating cancers after they've already occurred, of

8
00:00:19.700 --> 00:00:20.040
course.

9
00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:25.900
This is the science and health policy session on cancer

10
00:00:26.140 --> 00:00:29.000
prevention and screening for early-stage disease.

11
00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:33.820
I'm Gil Omenn from the University of Michigan and our Rogel Cancer Center.

12
00:00:35.020 --> 00:00:38.400
In this session, we bring together science, medicine, public health, and health

13
00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:39.020
policy

14
00:00:40.380 --> 00:00:44.330
to focus on a shared challenge: reduce the incidence and mortality

15
00:00:45.020 --> 00:00:45.820
of cancers.

16
00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:50.949
My disclosures are simple. I'm on several

17
00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:55.020
small, still early-stage companies from the University of Michigan,

18
00:00:55.180 --> 00:00:56.620
basically.

19
00:01:00.280 --> 00:01:03.340
There is a great opportunity to reduce the cancer burden

20
00:01:04.160 --> 00:01:06.160
in the United States and around the world.

21
00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:10.710
Cancers are leading causes of global morbidity and mortality.

22
00:01:12.370 --> 00:01:16.320
The message here is that incidence is largely attributable

23
00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:20.300
to modifiable risk factors. About 40% of

24
00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:24.100
cancer cases worldwide are preventable, according to the

25
00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:28.780
IARC, International Agency for Research on Cancer,

26
00:01:29.740 --> 00:01:33.000
the "Nature Medicine" 2026 paper recently published.

27
00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:37.680
Globally, nearly half of preventable cancer cases involve lung,

28
00:01:38.460 --> 00:01:39.980
stomach, and cervix.

29
00:01:42.900 --> 00:01:46.720
The two leading contributors, of course, are by far smoking

30
00:01:46.820 --> 00:01:50.320
and then nine different viral infections

31
00:01:51.460 --> 00:01:54.620
with the other conditions well known to you listed here.

32
00:01:56.840 --> 00:02:00.130
Environmental includes 13 different occupational exposures

33
00:02:00.680 --> 00:02:02.040
monitored by IARC.

34
00:02:04.100 --> 00:02:06.660
Cancer mortality can be reduced by prevention,

35
00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:09.320
by screening for early detection,

36
00:02:10.120 --> 00:02:13.540
sometimes called interception, which is to capture a

37
00:02:13.580 --> 00:02:16.880
precancerous lesion before it becomes malignant,

38
00:02:19.320 --> 00:02:21.860
and of course, progress in treatment as well.

39
00:02:23.420 --> 00:02:27.380
Prevention and screening were responsible for 80%

40
00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:29.660
of the deaths averted

41
00:02:30.660 --> 00:02:30.900
in the

42
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.660
long period from 1975 to 2020.

43
00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:45.000
Estimates in 2023 of the percent of US population

44
00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:48.500
that are up to date on

45
00:02:48.560 --> 00:02:50.340
recommended cancer screening

46
00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:55.300
shows 80% for breast cancer screening, that's mammography,

47
00:02:57.040 --> 00:02:59.280
76% for cervical cancer,

48
00:03:00.980 --> 00:03:04.460
64%, may be rising still, for

49
00:03:04.540 --> 00:03:05.320
colorectal.

50
00:03:06.520 --> 00:03:08.400
You can see all of those

51
00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:13.020
in this slide here to the right.

52
00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:17.460
So breast has been moving up nicely and now been level for

53
00:03:17.640 --> 00:03:19.500
25 years to almost 30 years.

54
00:03:20.380 --> 00:03:23.380
Colorectal continues to rise and is continuing further.

55
00:03:24.660 --> 00:03:27.680
But lung cancer screening, for which there's quite a large literature,

56
00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:32.220
is extremely low. We're going to hear about that in detail from Dr.

57
00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:32.740
Wood.

58
00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:38.950
Only 14% of cancers are currently detected through these

59
00:03:38.980 --> 00:03:41.080
recommended screening tests in the US.

60
00:03:41.720 --> 00:03:45.120
There is ample room for making a lot of progress.

61
00:03:47.380 --> 00:03:51.370
Gaps in cancer screening affected by age-related guidelines,

62
00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:52.840
which are in some flux,

63
00:03:53.880 --> 00:03:54.940
insurance status,

64
00:03:55.860 --> 00:03:57.500
race, and socioeconomic

65
00:03:58.300 --> 00:03:58.700
status.

66
00:03:59.900 --> 00:04:03.180
There's a particular approach to mention here developed at the University of

67
00:04:03.220 --> 00:04:07.049
Michigan, my colleagues Mark Fendrick and others,

68
00:04:07.820 --> 00:04:10.140
called value-based insurance design,

69
00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:14.910
where the out-of-pocket expenses for medical services

70
00:04:15.800 --> 00:04:18.620
are reduced as much as possible, even turned negative.

71
00:04:18.661 --> 00:04:22.460
That say, pay the patient to do certain things we think

72
00:04:22.469 --> 00:04:26.460
have such a big payoff for them and for society that we

73
00:04:26.500 --> 00:04:30.480
need to encourage them further to take advantage of advances from research,

74
00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:35.480
and charge more for things we're trying to discourage.

75
00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:38.480
Medicaid eligibility restrictions

76
00:04:39.360 --> 00:04:43.200
and the FY25 Appropriations Act, of course, are in the

77
00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:44.160
opposite direction,

78
00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:49.460
leading to an estimated million missed cancer screenings

79
00:04:50.020 --> 00:04:52.680
and clinical preventive services over the next two years.

80
00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:58.440
So the policy opportunities include more tobacco

81
00:04:58.480 --> 00:04:59.160
regulation,

82
00:05:00.020 --> 00:05:03.560
more community-level personalized interventions, including

83
00:05:04.120 --> 00:05:06.740
perhaps selected genetic testing, as we'll hear from Dr.

84
00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:07.630
Rebick,

85
00:05:08.760 --> 00:05:11.520
screening access for rural and underserved populations,

86
00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:14.920
and barriers to drug development.

87
00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:18.760
There's a vast effort going on in anti-cancer

88
00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:19.810
drug development,

89
00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:23.740
and we could make a lot of progress, I still hope,

90
00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:25.770
for chemoprevention

91
00:05:26.580 --> 00:05:30.140
at early stages and at pre-malignant stages.

92
00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:35.220
To give you some idea how this was viewed 45 years ago,

93
00:05:36.500 --> 00:05:38.950
we organized, my colleagues and I around the country,

94
00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:43.580
the CARROT trial, beta carotene and retinol efficacy trial.

95
00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:48.469
You see the details here, 18,000 high-risk smokers, former smokers,

96
00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:50.840
and asbestos-exposed shipyard workers.

97
00:05:51.660 --> 00:05:55.560
The results, this was a time when cereal boxes said, "Laced with

98
00:05:55.600 --> 00:05:57.580
beta carotene," minus the laced.

99
00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:02.100
Contains beta carotene.And the

100
00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:06.260
vitamin supplement crowd was very keen about this.

101
00:06:06.540 --> 00:06:10.500
We thought it was good epidemiological association basis for

102
00:06:10.580 --> 00:06:13.020
starting the trial, as did the NCI.

103
00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:17.980
But the result was 28% more lung cancer, 17% more

104
00:06:18.020 --> 00:06:21.600
lung cancer mortality, 26% more cardiovascular

105
00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:22.460
mortality.

106
00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:26.980
And if that might have left you quizzical, a

107
00:06:27.060 --> 00:06:30.990
simultaneous study in Finland with vitamin E and beta carotene,

108
00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:34.320
alpha-tocopherol and beta carotene, so ATBC,

109
00:06:35.460 --> 00:06:37.040
had similar results.

110
00:06:38.940 --> 00:06:42.840
Our goals today are to outline policy strategies to reduce

111
00:06:42.900 --> 00:06:46.500
major cancer risk factors, to explore innovative

112
00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:49.670
cancer prevention methods, hopefully including chemoprevention,

113
00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:54.480
discuss policy approaches to improving uptake of recommended

114
00:06:54.490 --> 00:06:55.110
screenings,

115
00:06:55.940 --> 00:06:59.820
highlight community and behavioral interventions, and promote

116
00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:03.100
policy mechanisms that can address disparities.

117
00:07:04.340 --> 00:07:07.680
Our session has a wonderful group of panelists.

118
00:07:07.700 --> 00:07:10.060
I'm delighted to be part of this panel with them,

119
00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:14.840
and the names are all shown here. I will start with Dr.

120
00:07:15.060 --> 00:07:18.640
Suchitra Krishnan-Sarin from Yale Department of

121
00:07:18.880 --> 00:07:19.480
Psychiatry.

122
00:07:20.380 --> 00:07:20.720
Welcome.

123
00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:32.300
Thank you.

124
00:07:34.040 --> 00:07:36.000
Do I just click to move ahead? Is that the...

125
00:07:37.780 --> 00:07:37.810
Right arrow.

126
00:07:37.810 --> 00:07:39.120
Ah, right arrow. Got it.

127
00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:43.620
Okay. Well, thank you for inviting me to speak at this very

128
00:07:43.660 --> 00:07:44.220
important

129
00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:48.940
panel. I'm going to take you through a whirlwind about tobacco

130
00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:52.880
regulation and interventions, but I'm happy to answer any questions at

131
00:07:52.940 --> 00:07:54.080
the end that you might have.

132
00:07:55.120 --> 00:07:58.660
I do not have any disclosures. My work is funded by the FDA and NIH,

133
00:07:58.820 --> 00:08:02.440
so anything that I say today are my own views and do not represent their

134
00:08:02.480 --> 00:08:03.340
official views.

135
00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:07.580
So to start out, I know I'm preaching to the choir here, and you've already heard

136
00:08:07.660 --> 00:08:09.400
tobacco is the leading cause of cancer.

137
00:08:10.140 --> 00:08:13.500
Roughly 80% of lung cancers and many other cancers.

138
00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:17.760
Oral cancer from smokeless tobacco use is very common, and it also

139
00:08:17.800 --> 00:08:19.660
causes diseases in many other organs.

140
00:08:19.740 --> 00:08:23.380
Now, if anybody is interested, this is a really nice schema that is

141
00:08:23.400 --> 00:08:27.340
presented in this paper on the relationship between smokeless tobacco use

142
00:08:27.360 --> 00:08:31.320
and cigarette smoking and the different mechanisms by which it causes cancer, and I

143
00:08:31.340 --> 00:08:34.321
would encourage you to take a look at it.

144
00:08:34.420 --> 00:08:38.000
So these are cigarette and cigar prevalence rates, and I have to say, in the US, we

145
00:08:38.040 --> 00:08:41.441
have been doing pretty good. We are on a downward trend.

146
00:08:41.540 --> 00:08:45.040
You see the rates decreasing. We are headed towards the Healthy People

147
00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:48.400
2030 goal of 5%, and I hope we reach it.

148
00:08:48.940 --> 00:08:50.900
But we are headed in the right direction.

149
00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:54.660
And on the right panel, you see cigar use rates, which have remained pretty

150
00:08:54.940 --> 00:08:55.360
flat.

151
00:08:56.240 --> 00:08:59.460
This is smokeless tobacco use. This is very localized.

152
00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:03.600
Certain states have more smokeless tobacco use than other states, but it's

153
00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:07.120
also kind of remained flat. And then on the right side, you see

154
00:09:07.160 --> 00:09:10.760
e-cigarette use. E-cigarettes appeared on the market around 2009,

155
00:09:11.180 --> 00:09:14.480
and we started monitoring their use since then, and you can see a steady increase

156
00:09:14.580 --> 00:09:15.740
in use of these products.

157
00:09:16.780 --> 00:09:19.540
This is not a US problem. It's a global problem.

158
00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:23.580
Globally, the rates of use of cigarette is much higher in many other

159
00:09:23.620 --> 00:09:24.620
countries and regions,

160
00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:29.370
and they are all decreasing except for certain regions that you can see here, like

161
00:09:29.400 --> 00:09:32.360
the Eastern Mediterranean and Western Pacific, which is actually going up.

162
00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:39.160
Okay, so I'm going to switch now. Every country I showed you has their own set of

163
00:09:39.460 --> 00:09:42.960
regulations around tobacco. I'm going to switch and tell you about what we have

164
00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:44.680
been doing in the US all these years.

165
00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:48.880
We've, I think, had a phenomenal set of regulations over the

166
00:09:48.940 --> 00:09:49.760
past

167
00:09:50.900 --> 00:09:54.380
many years, starting in the 1900s and so on, which

168
00:09:54.840 --> 00:09:58.790
have addressed tobacco use, especially cigarette use, including things

169
00:09:58.840 --> 00:10:02.600
like broadcast ad bans and cigarette taxes, which have really helped to decrease

170
00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:06.560
the use of cigarettes. Now, the most

171
00:10:06.620 --> 00:10:10.240
recent entrant into this is the Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco

172
00:10:10.340 --> 00:10:14.320
Control Act, which was signed by President Obama into

173
00:10:14.340 --> 00:10:18.260
law in 2009. This, for the first time, gave the

174
00:10:18.340 --> 00:10:22.070
FDA the authority to regulate tobacco products and

175
00:10:22.120 --> 00:10:26.000
nicotine products. Now, I want to give you some brief

176
00:10:26.060 --> 00:10:29.620
information on how this differs from the FDA's ability to

177
00:10:29.680 --> 00:10:33.539
regulate drugs. Drugs, as you know, are approved by a safe and effective

178
00:10:33.660 --> 00:10:37.550
standard. So is the drug safe? Does it have an efficacy in a particular condition?

179
00:10:38.100 --> 00:10:41.880
As opposed to the Center for Tobacco Products in FDA regulates tobacco

180
00:10:41.960 --> 00:10:44.020
products by a public health standard.

181
00:10:44.089 --> 00:10:47.780
So is the presence of these products in the market good for all of

182
00:10:47.800 --> 00:10:51.780
public health? And they do this through two routes specified on the

183
00:10:51.800 --> 00:10:55.060
right side. They give marketing approval called Pre-market,

184
00:10:55.080 --> 00:10:58.840
PMTAs, or they give a modified tobacco risk approval,

185
00:10:59.180 --> 00:11:02.960
which basically means that the product has a reduced risk compared to other

186
00:11:02.980 --> 00:11:06.500
products in the market. Most of the tobacco companies today get

187
00:11:06.580 --> 00:11:10.180
marketing approval, which basically allows them to market the product in the US.

188
00:11:11.220 --> 00:11:14.420
These are all the tobacco products regulated by the US FDA.

189
00:11:14.520 --> 00:11:18.360
You see some familiar faces here. Some new ones like the oral nicotine

190
00:11:18.440 --> 00:11:21.730
pouches and these heat sticks, which you're going to see a lot on the market very

191
00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:26.110
soon, which are products which burn tobacco at a lower temperature

192
00:11:26.120 --> 00:11:29.580
than cigarettes and therefore presumably produce less carcinogens.

193
00:11:30.660 --> 00:11:34.140
Now, I'm going to use e-cigarettes as an example of how the FDA does this work.

194
00:11:34.260 --> 00:11:34.440
So,

195
00:11:35.380 --> 00:11:37.830
e-cigarettes, as you know, came on the market in 2009.

196
00:11:37.980 --> 00:11:41.940
On the left side, you see a whole list of products which have

197
00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.620
actually received marketing approval from the FDA.

198
00:11:45.220 --> 00:11:48.400
But despite this, there is a huge unauthorized product

199
00:11:48.500 --> 00:11:52.340
market. You get a lot of products which are not approved by the FDA in any

200
00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:56.000
way, and there are also constantly emerging novel products like

201
00:11:56.560 --> 00:12:00.080
e-cigarettes with video games in them, or these other products which

202
00:12:00.820 --> 00:12:04.540
blatantly challenge FDA regulations because they say they don't contain

203
00:12:04.600 --> 00:12:08.280
nicotine, but they contain an analog of nicotine called metatine, and

204
00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:10.600
therefore they are not subject to the same kind of

205
00:12:10.640 --> 00:12:14.324
regulation.The concerns with these kind of

206
00:12:14.384 --> 00:12:17.804
unregulated market is youth appeal, obviously.

207
00:12:17.844 --> 00:12:21.544
This figure shows you how youth use of cigarettes went up

208
00:12:21.564 --> 00:12:25.534
significantly after Juul first appeared on the market around 2014, 2015.

209
00:12:26.104 --> 00:12:29.744
And then we have fortunately had a lot of regulations which have brought youth use

210
00:12:29.784 --> 00:12:33.284
down. There is a lot of concern about health outcomes related to

211
00:12:33.304 --> 00:12:35.344
e-cigarettes. This literature is just emerging.

212
00:12:36.204 --> 00:12:39.094
I would encourage you to take a look at this review paper, which just came out,

213
00:12:39.124 --> 00:12:42.874
which points out that the potential for carcinogenesis from e-cigarettes is not

214
00:12:42.904 --> 00:12:46.664
just nicotine, but all the other constituents of the e-cigarette, which can be

215
00:12:46.724 --> 00:12:50.164
related to DNA damage and inflammation.

216
00:12:50.224 --> 00:12:51.904
But e-cigarettes also have benefit.

217
00:12:52.333 --> 00:12:55.704
There are good clinical trials, and there is a Cochrane review which shows that

218
00:12:55.744 --> 00:12:57.994
e-cigarettes do help smokers quit smoking,

219
00:12:59.084 --> 00:13:03.064
and they are relatively safe. So when the FDA considers a product like this, they

220
00:13:03.124 --> 00:13:05.324
have to do a risk-benefit assessment.

221
00:13:06.124 --> 00:13:09.844
On the right side, you have it could help cigarette smokers quit.

222
00:13:10.004 --> 00:13:12.264
It could reduce disease risk and morbidity.

223
00:13:12.984 --> 00:13:15.144
But on the other hand, you have to consider the harms.

224
00:13:15.484 --> 00:13:19.464
It could lead to initiation of nicotine use and addiction, or in adults, very

225
00:13:19.584 --> 00:13:23.364
commonly, we see a lot of dual use, where many adult smokers don't

226
00:13:23.384 --> 00:13:26.744
necessarily quit cigarettes but use e-cigarettes and cigarettes along

227
00:13:27.304 --> 00:13:28.704
with each other at the same time.

228
00:13:29.764 --> 00:13:31.604
So what can we do? Last few slides.

229
00:13:32.744 --> 00:13:36.524
I would suggest we should all really go back and follow the treatment

230
00:13:36.584 --> 00:13:39.984
guidelines that we have. The WHO came out with a great set of

231
00:13:40.984 --> 00:13:44.644
guidelines in 2024, which recommended that all healthcare

232
00:13:44.664 --> 00:13:48.604
facilities should include an assessment of tobacco use status and use

233
00:13:48.624 --> 00:13:52.564
of tobacco interventions. They recommended training all healthcare providers

234
00:13:52.604 --> 00:13:56.504
on delivery of evidence-based interventions and provide them at low

235
00:13:56.584 --> 00:13:59.184
or reduced costs. So we definitely need to consider this.

236
00:13:59.964 --> 00:14:02.784
They also provided guidelines for what you could use.

237
00:14:02.924 --> 00:14:06.344
There are many guidelines for how brief interventions work.

238
00:14:06.704 --> 00:14:10.384
Even something as short as 30 seconds to three minutes can have an impact on a

239
00:14:10.404 --> 00:14:12.204
person's motivation to quit.

240
00:14:13.204 --> 00:14:15.444
And of course, more intensive support for those who need it.

241
00:14:15.884 --> 00:14:19.704
And the WHO recommends varenicline or Chantix, nicotine replacement

242
00:14:19.764 --> 00:14:23.584
therapy, bupropion, and cytisine, which is a nicotine analog, as

243
00:14:23.664 --> 00:14:25.323
adjuncts for smoking cessation.

244
00:14:26.484 --> 00:14:29.984
But I want to point out that there are still huge disparities

245
00:14:30.924 --> 00:14:34.684
in terms of access to treatment, in terms of whether people use

246
00:14:34.744 --> 00:14:38.604
interventions or not. On this slide, you see that almost any smoker you

247
00:14:38.664 --> 00:14:42.204
talk to will say they want to quit smoking, and that's what the extreme left

248
00:14:42.304 --> 00:14:45.904
bars show you on all these figures. But look at the bars in the center.

249
00:14:46.544 --> 00:14:50.444
Very few of them actually manage to quit, and that is partly because

250
00:14:50.924 --> 00:14:54.124
if you keep moving along the right side of this figure, you can see that

251
00:14:55.284 --> 00:14:58.844
the number receiving quit assistance and the number that actually use counseling or

252
00:14:58.884 --> 00:15:01.144
medication goes down dramatically.

253
00:15:01.204 --> 00:15:04.544
And this is particularly the case in Black or African American

254
00:15:04.584 --> 00:15:06.724
communities and in Hispanic communities.

255
00:15:06.804 --> 00:15:10.644
So we really need to do better because our interventions are

256
00:15:10.724 --> 00:15:12.284
not reaching many communities.

257
00:15:13.584 --> 00:15:17.474
So this is my final slide. We need to do better, utilize all clinical

258
00:15:17.564 --> 00:15:19.284
touchpoints to address tobacco use.

259
00:15:19.744 --> 00:15:23.444
I would really encourage everybody in this conference to go beyond yes/no,

260
00:15:23.584 --> 00:15:26.924
please. Don't just ask, "Are you a smoker or not?" Try to get some

261
00:15:27.004 --> 00:15:30.353
information on how much they are smoking, how long they've been smoking,

262
00:15:30.424 --> 00:15:32.884
because all that can be used in interventions.

263
00:15:33.424 --> 00:15:37.184
Address disparities and finally, encourage people to quit all

264
00:15:37.204 --> 00:15:40.674
tobacco products. And if they want to use e-cigarettes, support them,

265
00:15:41.404 --> 00:15:45.384
but want them not to overuse, quit completely, and plan to quit

266
00:15:45.424 --> 00:15:49.244
e-cigarettes as well. So I know I've exceeded my time, but I'm going to

267
00:15:49.304 --> 00:15:50.064
stop now.

268
00:15:55.224 --> 00:15:58.964
Thank you very much. We will hold Q&amp;A

269
00:15:59.304 --> 00:16:01.304
for after all the speakers have spoken.

270
00:16:02.204 --> 00:16:05.144
You might want to make some notes. It's hard to keep everything in mind for

271
00:16:06.084 --> 00:16:06.654
30 minutes.

272
00:16:08.284 --> 00:16:12.224
Doug Wood is Chairman of the Department of Surgery at the University of Washington

273
00:16:12.304 --> 00:16:16.284
and a senior surgeon and leader at the Fred Hutch Cancer Research

274
00:16:16.364 --> 00:16:19.404
Center. Doug is going to talk about lung cancer screening.

275
00:16:22.384 --> 00:16:25.124
Thank you, Dr. Ohman, and it's great to be part of this panel.

276
00:16:25.224 --> 00:16:27.494
And, I have no disclosures,

277
00:16:28.504 --> 00:16:29.224
unfortunately.

278
00:16:30.884 --> 00:16:33.724
But I would start with acknowledging

