00:17:20.424 --> 00:17:24.204
and I think the people in this audience are familiar that lung

293
00:17:24.264 --> 00:17:28.085
cancer is by far the most common cause of cancer death.

294
00:17:28.164 --> 00:17:32.084
In fact, it's about the same as the next four

295
00:17:32.144 --> 00:17:35.964
cancer deaths combined. And in fact, if

296
00:17:36.044 --> 00:17:39.944
you look at that gold bar that is the sixth most common cause

297
00:17:39.984 --> 00:17:43.504
of cancer death, I think you'd be surprised to know that that

298
00:17:43.624 --> 00:17:46.484
is lung cancer in never smokers.

299
00:17:47.904 --> 00:17:51.484
The sixth most common cause of cancer death is lung cancer in never

300
00:17:51.564 --> 00:17:55.024
smokers. And so we're here talking about

301
00:17:55.044 --> 00:17:58.444
prevention and screening. I'm concentrating on screening,

302
00:17:58.484 --> 00:18:02.284
and if we look 16 years ago, we had screening

303
00:18:02.344 --> 00:18:05.564
for many of the major cancers, but not for lung cancer.

304
00:18:05.784 --> 00:18:09.464
There was no screening for lung cancer in 2010.

305
00:18:10.404 --> 00:18:14.284
And this audience is also familiar with the National Lung Screening Trial

306
00:18:15.624 --> 00:18:17.374
that came out in 2010,

307
00:18:18.844 --> 00:18:22.548
thatDemonstrated a 20% mortality

308
00:18:22.608 --> 00:18:26.448
reduction from low-dose CT in those that were high risk for

309
00:18:26.528 --> 00:18:27.387
lung cancer.

310
00:18:28.468 --> 00:18:31.008
And quickly following that were guidelines.

311
00:18:31.188 --> 00:18:35.048
This was the first guidelines produced about lung cancer screening

312
00:18:35.128 --> 00:18:38.988
for the National Comprehensive Cancer Network, or NCCN, that

313
00:18:39.048 --> 00:18:42.968
made recommendations for who should be screened after the publication

314
00:18:43.428 --> 00:18:44.688
of the NLST.

315
00:18:46.328 --> 00:18:47.728
And this led to a,

316
00:18:48.748 --> 00:18:52.468
what there's not time to discuss, but a pretty complicated and prolonged

317
00:18:52.607 --> 00:18:56.448
policy process that took about five years to

318
00:18:56.568 --> 00:19:00.248
actually have implementation of coverage for lung cancer

319
00:19:00.328 --> 00:19:04.248
screening in private insurance because of recommendations

320
00:19:04.268 --> 00:19:07.928
from USPSTF, and

321
00:19:08.208 --> 00:19:12.008
publicly insured with Medicare beneficiaries, both

322
00:19:12.068 --> 00:19:16.048
occurring at the beginning of 2015, just 11

323
00:19:16.088 --> 00:19:16.748
years ago.

324
00:19:18.128 --> 00:19:22.028
So that's a great advance. The largest cause of cancer death

325
00:19:22.508 --> 00:19:26.488
now has a screening modality, but unfortunately,

326
00:19:26.648 --> 00:19:30.628
that only captures about a quarter of the individuals that are going

327
00:19:30.648 --> 00:19:34.488
to die of lung cancer. So a great step forward, but missing

328
00:19:34.548 --> 00:19:38.368
about 75% of the opportunity

329
00:19:38.408 --> 00:19:41.188
for early cancer detection in lung cancer patients.

330
00:19:42.688 --> 00:19:46.548
So fortunately, we've had additional data and additional opportunity

331
00:19:46.688 --> 00:19:50.548
to expand the screening recommendations.

332
00:19:51.068 --> 00:19:54.808
NCCN did two things. It both simplified

333
00:19:54.928 --> 00:19:58.468
and extended the screening recommendations.

334
00:19:58.488 --> 00:19:59.468
Both are important.

335
00:20:00.348 --> 00:20:03.788
The improvement of the inclusion criteria,

336
00:20:04.268 --> 00:20:07.788
but also the simplification to make it easier for

337
00:20:07.908 --> 00:20:10.108
application of primary care providers.

338
00:20:11.028 --> 00:20:14.868
And this actually was also followed, and this time in a

339
00:20:14.928 --> 00:20:17.968
shorter fashion, by USPSTF in

340
00:20:18.128 --> 00:20:21.588
2021, changing their recommendations to be

341
00:20:21.668 --> 00:20:25.328
somewhat similar, not completely to the NCCN, they're

342
00:20:25.388 --> 00:20:29.118
still more complicated, and Medicare followed a year later

343
00:20:29.268 --> 00:20:32.348
in 2022. So those changes in

344
00:20:32.508 --> 00:20:36.248
2015 were then further improved upon in

345
00:20:36.408 --> 00:20:38.428
2021 and 2022.

346
00:20:39.828 --> 00:20:43.688
This shows the impact of the implementation of lung cancer

347
00:20:43.768 --> 00:20:47.618
screening, and you can see an inflection point when we started having

348
00:20:47.668 --> 00:20:51.228
coverage for screening with more individuals being

349
00:20:51.288 --> 00:20:54.408
identified with early-stage cancers and a

350
00:20:54.488 --> 00:20:57.958
corresponding fewer number of individuals being

351
00:20:58.008 --> 00:21:01.768
identified with late-stage lung cancer, exactly what we are

352
00:21:01.828 --> 00:21:05.488
trying to accomplish with cancer early detection.

353
00:21:07.668 --> 00:21:11.378
And remarkably, that inflection is

354
00:21:11.448 --> 00:21:14.948
with only 19% of individuals being

355
00:21:14.988 --> 00:21:15.488
screened.

356
00:21:16.918 --> 00:21:20.248
This paper from the American Cancer Society just a few months ago

357
00:21:20.728 --> 00:21:24.068
modeled that that 19% still results in a

358
00:21:24.148 --> 00:21:27.668
significant number of lives saved, about 15,000 lives

359
00:21:27.708 --> 00:21:29.848
saved over a five-year period.

360
00:21:30.828 --> 00:21:34.228
But imagine what we could do if we had a

361
00:21:34.268 --> 00:21:37.808
better inclusion of those individuals.

362
00:21:37.868 --> 00:21:41.808
We could quadruple that and have over 60,000 lives

363
00:21:41.888 --> 00:21:45.788
saved in five years. And if we expanded the

364
00:21:45.848 --> 00:21:49.138
smoking definition, that would be another

365
00:21:49.528 --> 00:21:53.448
26,000, so an approximate 90,000 lives that

366
00:21:53.528 --> 00:21:57.368
could be saved if we improve the inclusion criteria and

367
00:21:57.588 --> 00:21:59.388
access for lung cancer screening.

368
00:21:59.938 --> 00:22:03.888
And this paper recommended revisiting the current eligibility

369
00:22:03.948 --> 00:22:05.528
requirements as a result.

370
00:22:07.508 --> 00:22:11.188
There are many reasons why the lung cancer screening

371
00:22:11.248 --> 00:22:15.068
rate is still low, from the fact of it's

372
00:22:15.108 --> 00:22:18.618
still early in the adoption, but also stigma and

373
00:22:18.708 --> 00:22:22.368
nihilism have been factors that have limited access to lung

374
00:22:22.388 --> 00:22:26.328
cancer care. But I'm going to concentrate on this aspect

375
00:22:26.388 --> 00:22:29.948
of complicated and restrictive inclusion criteria,

376
00:22:30.628 --> 00:22:33.968
and I don't have time of course to go through all the data around these, but

377
00:22:34.008 --> 00:22:37.648
there's three. One is to change the

378
00:22:37.688 --> 00:22:41.628
recommendation that limits lung cancer screening for those that

379
00:22:41.668 --> 00:22:44.108
have stopped smoking for more than 15 years,

380
00:22:45.248 --> 00:22:48.608
to eliminate the upper age limit of 80 that

381
00:22:48.768 --> 00:22:52.288
exists in our policy but does not exist in the

382
00:22:52.368 --> 00:22:55.928
NCCN guidelines, and maybe most

383
00:22:55.968 --> 00:22:59.028
importantly, simplify the smoking metric.

384
00:22:59.408 --> 00:23:03.388
We're all used to talking about pack years, but if we use smoking

385
00:23:03.428 --> 00:23:06.648
duration rather than pack years, it's easier to

386
00:23:06.708 --> 00:23:10.408
identify, and it turns out that it more accurately

387
00:23:10.868 --> 00:23:14.468
picks up the individuals that are at risk for lung cancer and more

388
00:23:14.588 --> 00:23:17.788
equitably in terms of minority individuals.

389
00:23:19.008 --> 00:23:22.708
And if we weigh the balances of we don't want to screen

390
00:23:22.768 --> 00:23:26.408
low-risk individuals, there's harms of that, and we want to

391
00:23:26.468 --> 00:23:30.308
screen high-risk individuals, and I'm trying to emphasize that if

392
00:23:30.348 --> 00:23:33.898
we're only screening 19% of high-risk individuals,

393
00:23:34.508 --> 00:23:38.268
that is our priority. That is where we have to pay our attention

394
00:23:38.278 --> 00:23:42.108
now, and this is the reason. The curve on the

395
00:23:42.168 --> 00:23:45.968
left is a normal lung cancer survival curve of five

396
00:23:46.068 --> 00:23:49.928
years, 22%. The curve on the right is a

397
00:23:49.948 --> 00:23:53.788
lung cancer survival curve from the International Early Lung Cancer

398
00:23:53.968 --> 00:23:57.868
Action project, 84% because of lung cancer screening.

399
00:23:58.368 --> 00:24:02.248
There's few interventions that we have that result in a true

400
00:24:02.388 --> 00:24:04.708
inversion of a survival curve.

401
00:24:05.668 --> 00:24:09.608
And I'll come back to how I started and make this point that

402
00:24:09.688 --> 00:24:12.648
we have had successes in prevention and early

403
00:24:12.728 --> 00:24:16.288
detection with decreasing mortality rates in the

404
00:24:16.328 --> 00:24:19.688
United States, and over the past 10 years, those

405
00:24:19.708 --> 00:24:23.528
decreasing mortality rates have been largely driven by

406
00:24:23.568 --> 00:24:27.276
decreasing mortality in lung cancer.And the

407
00:24:27.316 --> 00:24:30.896
goal is to try to take more lung cancer victims

408
00:24:31.216 --> 00:24:33.336
and help them become lung cancer survivors.

409
00:24:34.276 --> 00:24:34.696
Thank you.

410
00:24:41.616 --> 00:24:44.856
Well, that's a very compelling take-home message.

411
00:24:45.356 --> 00:24:48.536
There's so much more that could be gained by following your

412
00:24:49.276 --> 00:24:50.516
analysis and advice.

413
00:24:51.536 --> 00:24:53.776
Our next speaker is Dr. Tim Rebbeck.

414
00:24:54.596 --> 00:24:58.556
He is professor of Cancer Prevention and Epidemiology

415
00:24:58.576 --> 00:25:01.396
at the Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health,

416
00:25:02.616 --> 00:25:06.396
and his focus is on precision oncology, that's a

417
00:25:06.436 --> 00:25:09.876
precision prevention and personalized medicine.

418
00:25:10.756 --> 00:25:11.556
Thank you.

419
00:25:12.796 --> 00:25:13.996
Well, thank you very much, everybody.

420
00:25:14.046 --> 00:25:16.026
And I'd like to pick up on the comments that Dr.

421
00:25:16.276 --> 00:25:19.156
Wood just made, that what we're trying to do is

422
00:25:20.856 --> 00:25:24.376
maximize the benefits and minimize the harms of

423
00:25:24.396 --> 00:25:27.856
prevention. And when I talk about prevention here, I'm going to use that generic

424
00:25:27.896 --> 00:25:31.636
term, but I mean prevention, primary prevention, early detection, et

425
00:25:31.716 --> 00:25:34.816
cetera, as I think all of those things fit in here.

426
00:25:34.876 --> 00:25:38.416
I have no disclosures. So what is this precision

427
00:25:38.456 --> 00:25:41.716
prevention concept? So it adapts the principles of precision

428
00:25:41.796 --> 00:25:45.116
medicine to prevent cancer or detect it

429
00:25:45.176 --> 00:25:49.056
early. It moves from this one-size-fits-all model, which you've

430
00:25:49.116 --> 00:25:52.376
just heard about, for the most part, everybody should stop smoking.

431
00:25:52.456 --> 00:25:55.706
Everybody should limit their exposure to these carcinogens,

432
00:25:56.276 --> 00:26:00.116
to finding the right intervention for the right person at the right time.

433
00:26:00.876 --> 00:26:04.636
And we believe that the increased net benefit for those at

434
00:26:04.716 --> 00:26:08.156
highest risk through more intensive or earlier interventions will

435
00:26:08.236 --> 00:26:09.376
maximize the benefit,

436
00:26:10.256 --> 00:26:13.616
as long as we're able to reduce the harms, and

437
00:26:14.156 --> 00:26:17.576
minimize the resource usage for lower risk

438
00:26:17.656 --> 00:26:21.576
individuals. So it's really tailoring the strategies, so that one

439
00:26:21.676 --> 00:26:25.456
size does not fit all. And what we hope to be able to do is

440
00:26:25.516 --> 00:26:28.976
provide a framework that integrates novel tools, and that can

441
00:26:29.056 --> 00:26:32.186
be risk stratification, adaptive risk,

442
00:26:32.456 --> 00:26:36.436
biomarkers, imaging, novel liquid biopsy, multi-cancer

443
00:26:36.515 --> 00:26:39.016
early detection tests in order to achieve this.

444
00:26:39.056 --> 00:26:42.946
Some of these things will not be appropriate for everyone in the population, but

445
00:26:43.436 --> 00:26:46.676
if we can find those people who are going to benefit from some of these novel,

446
00:26:46.696 --> 00:26:50.336
perhaps more expensive, but more beneficial and less harmful tools,

447
00:26:50.696 --> 00:26:51.216
that's our goal.

448
00:26:52.416 --> 00:26:54.906
So the features of this kind of precision prevention,

449
00:26:55.836 --> 00:26:58.096
we need risk prediction and stratification.

450
00:26:58.136 --> 00:27:01.876
We have to figure out who these people are, who are at elevated

451
00:27:01.936 --> 00:27:05.116
risk. And to do that, we need large

452
00:27:05.796 --> 00:27:09.636
epidemiological studies that provide us information that

453
00:27:09.645 --> 00:27:12.476
accurately define who's going to have

454
00:27:13.496 --> 00:27:16.906
a cancer, but particularly a lethal cancer, a cancer that needs

455
00:27:16.936 --> 00:27:20.876
intervention. Ideally, we'd like to have a good mechanistic foundation.

456
00:27:20.916 --> 00:27:24.796
And I think Dr. Ullman's comment about the carrot in ATBC studies is a

457
00:27:24.836 --> 00:27:28.316
great example, that if we'd had better, not only, but if we'd had better

458
00:27:28.476 --> 00:27:31.896
mechanistic foundation, maybe we would've avoided some of the harms that would've

459
00:27:31.956 --> 00:27:35.276
come. We'd love to hear more about the concept of that.

460
00:27:35.676 --> 00:27:39.636
But we think that in a precision prevention approach,

461
00:27:39.736 --> 00:27:43.336
we should be able to use mechanistic and biological knowledge

462
00:27:43.796 --> 00:27:47.296
about carcinogenesis and who's at risk in order to develop the

463
00:27:47.316 --> 00:27:50.276
interventions that are going to be most likely to work and cause the least

464
00:27:50.336 --> 00:27:53.946
harm. We know that individuals have response

465
00:27:53.996 --> 00:27:57.816
heterogeneity. We can think about this as pharmacogenetics, but it goes well

466
00:27:57.836 --> 00:28:01.056
beyond that, that interventions are going to have different efficacies and

467
00:28:01.116 --> 00:28:04.996
toxicities in different groups. And we need to think about what those risk-benefit

468
00:28:05.076 --> 00:28:08.936
ratios are going to be. We don't want to just increase

469
00:28:09.676 --> 00:28:12.216
the intervention, the intensity of the intervention.

470
00:28:12.256 --> 00:28:15.576
We also want to tailor those to match the preventive

471
00:28:15.676 --> 00:28:18.436
strategy to individual risk tiers and again,

472
00:28:18.896 --> 00:28:22.776
minimize harm. We need to have optimized timing

473
00:28:22.836 --> 00:28:26.776
to intervene at the right point in the carcinogenesis process, and this

474
00:28:26.836 --> 00:28:30.106
might require updating. This was going to require new data, but it also might

475
00:28:30.116 --> 00:28:33.996
require the individual's risk information to be updated

476
00:28:34.036 --> 00:28:37.976
over time. So this is where a risk adaptive approach really

477
00:28:38.016 --> 00:28:38.675
is important.

478
00:28:39.676 --> 00:28:42.806
So what you can see in this figure is that there's a

479
00:28:44.335 --> 00:28:48.176
continuum. So precision prevention, first of all,

480
00:28:48.296 --> 00:28:50.866
complements guideline-based strategies.

481
00:28:51.396 --> 00:28:55.296
So, colonoscopy, Pap smears, a low-dose

482
00:28:55.336 --> 00:28:58.936
CT screening for lung cancer are not to be taken

483
00:28:58.996 --> 00:29:02.756
away. But the risk adaptive and precision

484
00:29:02.836 --> 00:29:06.796
prevention approach will then tailor on top of those to understand the

485
00:29:06.836 --> 00:29:10.606
timing, the dose, the intervention intensity,

486
00:29:11.216 --> 00:29:14.716
and maybe add new interventions on top of the guideline-based

487
00:29:14.776 --> 00:29:15.366
strategies.

488
00:29:16.486 --> 00:29:18.556
So it's difficult to do this, as you can imagine.

489
00:29:18.596 --> 00:29:21.116
It sounds good to say, well, we're going to find the right people.

490
00:29:21.176 --> 00:29:23.606
We're going to spend our energy intervening in them.

491
00:29:23.636 --> 00:29:26.356
We're going to reduce the intensity of the intervention on others.

492
00:29:26.966 --> 00:29:30.676
But this means a few things. It means there's added complexity for

493
00:29:30.736 --> 00:29:32.456
patients and clinicians. So

494
00:29:33.616 --> 00:29:36.996
there's extra steps, there's risk assessment, there's communication, there's

495
00:29:37.016 --> 00:29:37.876
understanding

496
00:29:38.696 --> 00:29:41.476
why you're doing this more intensive screening, and

497
00:29:42.536 --> 00:29:45.156
that isn't easy in a healthcare setting,

498
00:29:45.236 --> 00:29:49.066
particularly in a primary care health setting where

499
00:29:49.096 --> 00:29:52.196
people are very busy and may not be paying attention to these things or have the

500
00:29:52.216 --> 00:29:55.996
bandwidth to do so. There are a lot of evidence gaps, so we would love to

