01:34:34.490 --> 01:34:35.610
screening that needed it.

1719
01:34:36.470 --> 01:34:40.270
So that's a separate issue than the one that you brought up, but

1720
01:34:40.350 --> 01:34:43.970
a point that I've tried to make with policy makers

1721
01:34:44.070 --> 01:34:48.050
in trying to be willing to be less perfect

1722
01:34:48.110 --> 01:34:52.030
in order to broaden the gates that we can get people

1723
01:34:52.130 --> 01:34:55.070
in for screening that can benefit from screening.

1724
01:34:55.670 --> 01:34:57.639
That's a great point. Yeah.

1725
01:34:57.810 --> 01:34:57.990
So

1726
01:34:58.790 --> 01:35:00.210
one thing I want to add is,

1727
01:35:01.310 --> 01:35:04.050
so you know the master settlement agreement that we are all discussing with the

1728
01:35:04.070 --> 01:35:07.370
tobacco industry was really meant to support

1729
01:35:07.810 --> 01:35:10.530
cessation services and health services for people.

1730
01:35:10.570 --> 01:35:14.440
That was the goal when the settlement was made and when they

1731
01:35:14.530 --> 01:35:18.410
argued it in court and the tobacco industry were providing monies to support

1732
01:35:18.470 --> 01:35:21.850
this. Did it go towards this issue? No.

1733
01:35:22.410 --> 01:35:26.160
It's really pitiful when you look at some of the states in terms of how much money

1734
01:35:26.610 --> 01:35:29.410
actually went towards this. And one of the things I have learned, which I didn't

1735
01:35:29.450 --> 01:35:33.430
